# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mtconnect
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] A CNC machine is a motorized maneuverable tool and often a motorized maneuverable platform, which are both controlled by a computer, according to specific input instructions.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Instructions are delivered to a CNC machine in the form of a sequential program of machine control instructions such as G-code and M-code, and then executed.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The program can be written by a person or, far more often, generated by graphical computer-aided design (CAD) or computer-aided manufacturing (CAM) software.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] In the case of 3D printers, the part to be printed is cross-sectioned into virtual "slices" before the instructions (or the program) are generated.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] CNC offers greatly increased productivity over non-computerized machining for repetitive production, where the machine must be manually controlled (e.g. using devices such as hand wheels or levers) or mechanically controlled by pre-fabricated pattern guides (see pantograph mill).
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] However, these advantages come at significant cost in terms of both capital expenditure and job setup time.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] For some prototyping and small batch jobs, a good machine operator can have parts finished to a high standard whilst a CNC workflow is still in setup.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] In modern CNC systems, the design of a mechanical part and its manufacturing program are highly automated.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The part's mechanical dimensions are defined using CAD software and then translated into manufacturing directives by CAM software.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The resulting directives are transformed (by "post processor" software) into the specific commands necessary for a particular machine to produce the component and then are loaded into the CNC machine.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Since any particular component might require the use of several different tools – drills, saws, touch probes etc. – modern machines often combine multiple tools into a single "cell".
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] In other installations, several different machines are used with an external controller and human or robotic operators that move the component from machine to machine.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] In either case, the series of steps needed to produce any part is highly automated and produces a part that meets every specification in the original CAD drawing, where each specification includes a tolerance.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] In numerical control systems, the position of the tool is defined by a set of instructions called the part program.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Positioning control is handled using either an open-loop or a closed-loop system.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] In an open-loop system, communication takes place in one direction only: from the controller to the motor.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] In a closed-loop system, feedback is provided to the controller so that it can correct for errors in position, velocity, and acceleration, which can arise due to variations in load or temperature.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Open-loop systems are generally cheaper but less accurate.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Stepper motors can be used in both types of systems, while servo motors can only be used in closed systems.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Motion is controlling multiple axes, normally at least two (X and Y), and a tool spindle that moves in the Z (depth).
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The position of the tool is driven by direct-drive stepper motors or servo motors to provide highly accurate movements, or in older designs, motors through a series of step-down gears.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Open-loop control works as long as the forces are kept small enough and speeds are not too great.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] On commercial metalworking machines, closed-loop controls are standard and required to provide the accuracy, speed, and repeatability demanded.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The G & M code positions are all based on a three-dimensional Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] This system is a typical plane often seen in mathematics when graphing.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] This system is required to map out the machine tool paths and any other kind of actions that need to happen in a specific coordinate.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Absolute coordinates are what are generally used more commonly for machines and represent the (0,0,0) point on the plane.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] This point is set on the stock material to give a starting point or "home position" before starting the actual machining.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] As the controller hardware evolved, the mills themselves also evolved.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] One change has been to enclose the entire mechanism in a large box as a safety measure (with safety glass in the doors to permit the operator to monitor the machine's function), often with additional safety interlocks to ensure the operator is far enough from the working piece for safe operation.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Most new CNC systems built today are 100% electronically controlled.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] CNC-like systems are used for any process that can be described as movements and operations.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] These include laser cutting, welding, friction stir welding, ultrasonic welding, flame and plasma cutting, bending, spinning, hole-punching, pinning, gluing, fabric cutting, sewing, tape and fiber placement, routing, picking and placing, and sawing.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] A mild crash may not damage the machine or tools but may damage the part being machined so that it must be scrapped.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Many CNC tools have no inherent sense of the absolute position of the table or tools when turned on.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] They must be manually "homed" or "zeroed" to have any reference to work from, and these limits are just for figuring out the location of the part to work with it and are no hard motion limit on the mechanism.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] It is often possible to drive the machine outside the physical bounds of its drive mechanism, resulting in a collision with itself or damage to the drive mechanism.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Many machines implement control parameters limiting axis motion past a certain limit in addition to physical limit switches.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] However, these parameters can often be changed by the operator.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Many CNC tools also do not know anything about their working environment.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Machines may have load sensing systems on spindle and axis drives, but some do not.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] They blindly follow the machining code provided and it is up to an operator to detect if a crash is either occurring or about to occur, and for the operator to manually abort the active process.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Machines equipped with load sensors can stop axis or spindle movement in response to an overload condition, but this does not prevent a crash from occurring.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] It may only limit the damage resulting from the crash.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Some crashes may not ever overload any axis or spindle drives.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] If the drive system is weaker than the machine's structural integrity, then the drive system simply pushes against the obstruction, and the drive motors "slip in place".
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The machine tool may not detect the collision or the slipping, so for example the tool should now be at 210mm on the X-axis, but is, in fact, at 32mm where it hit the obstruction and kept slipping.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] All of the next tool motions will be off by −178mm on the X-axis, and all future motions are now invalid, which may result in further collisions with clamps, vises, or the machine itself.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] This is common in open-loop stepper systems but is not possible in closed-loop systems unless mechanical slippage between the motor and drive mechanism has occurred.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Instead, in a closed-loop system, the machine will continue to attempt to move against the load until either the drive motor goes into an overload condition or a servo motor fails to get to the desired position.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Instead, most hobby CNC tools simply rely on the assumed accuracy of stepper motors that rotate a specific number of degrees in response to magnetic field changes.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] It is often assumed the stepper is perfectly accurate and never missteps, so tool position monitoring simply involves counting the number of pulses sent to the stepper over time.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] An alternate means of stepper position monitoring is usually not available, so crash or slip detection is not possible.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Commercial CNC metalworking machines use closed-loop feedback controls for axis movement.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] In a closed-loop system, the controller monitors the actual position of each axis with an absolute or incremental encoder.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Proper control programming will reduce the possibility of a crash, but it is still up to the operator and programmer to ensure that the machine is operated safely.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Although such simulation is not new, its accuracy and market penetration are changing considerably because of computing advancements.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Within the numerical systems of CNC programming, the code generator can assume that the controlled mechanism is always perfectly accurate, or that precision tolerances are identical for all cutting or movement directions.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] While the common use of ball screws on most modern NC machines eliminates the vast majority of backlash, it still must be taken into account.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] CNC tools with a large amount of mechanical backlash can still be highly precise if the drive or cutting mechanism is only driven to apply cutting force from one direction, and all driving systems are pressed tightly together in that one cutting direction.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] However, a CNC device with high backlash and a dull cutting tool can lead to cutter chatter and possible workpiece gouging.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The backlash also affects the precision of some operations involving axis movement reversals during cutting, such as the milling of a circle, where axis motion is sinusoidal.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] However, this can be compensated for if the amount of backlash is precisely known by linear encoders or manual measurement.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] This is similar to the manual machine tool method of clamping a micrometer onto a reference beam and adjusting the Vernier dial to zero using that object as the reference.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] G-codes are used to command specific movements of the machine, such as machine moves or drilling functions.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The majority of G-code programs start with a percent (%) symbol on the first line, then followed by an "O" with a numerical name for the program (i.e.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] "O0001") on the second line, then another percent (%) symbol on the last line of the program.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The format for a G-code is the letter G followed by two to three digits; for example G01.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] [Code Miscellaneous Functions (M-Code)].
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] M-codes are miscellaneous machine commands that do not command axis motion.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Having the correct speeds and feeds in the program provides for a more efficient and smoother product run.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Incorrect speeds and feeds will cause damage to the tool, machine spindle, and even the product.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The quickest and simplest way to find these numbers would be to use a calculator that can be found online.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] A formula can also be used to calculate the proper speeds and feeds for a material.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] These values can be found online or in Machinery's Handbook.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] The first NC machines were built in the 1940s and 1950s, based on existing tools that were modified with motors that moved the tool or part to follow points fed into the system on punched tape.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] These early servomechanisms were rapidly augmented with analog and digital computers, creating the modern CNC machine tools that have revolutionized machining processes.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] CNC plays an extensive role in the processing manufacturing field, not only the traditional milling and turning, other machines and equipment are also installed with the corresponding CNC, which makes the manufacturing industry in its support, greatly improving the quality and efficiency.
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Traditional subtractive manufacturing can be combined with additive manufacturing (3D printing) to create a new manufacturing method - hybrid additive subtractive manufacturing (HASM).
[src:mtconnect/computer-numerical-control] Another trend is the combination of AI, using a large number of sensors, with the goal of achieving flexible manufacturing.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:mtconnect/extensible-markup-language] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] A **machine tool** is a machine for handling or machining metal or other rigid materials, usually by cutting, boring, grinding, shearing, or other forms of deformations.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Machine tools employ some sort of tool that does the cutting or shaping.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] All machine tools have some means of constraining the workpiece and provide a guided movement of the parts of the machine.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Thus, the relative movement between the workpiece and the cutting tool (which is called the **toolpath**) is controlled or constrained by the machine to at least some extent, rather than being entirely "offhand" or "freehand".
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] It is a power-driven metal cutting machine which assists in managing the needed relative motion between cutting tool and the job that changes the size and shape of the job material.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The precise definition of the term *machine tool* varies among users.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] While all machine tools are "machines that help people to make things", not all factory machines are machine tools.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Today machine tools are typically powered other than by the human muscle (e.g., electrically, hydraulically, or via line shaft), used to make manufactured parts (components) in various ways that include cutting or certain other kinds of deformation.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] With their inherent precision, machine tools enabled the economical production of interchangeable parts.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] In this view of the definition, the term, arising at a time when all tools up till then had been hand tools, simply provided a label for "tools that were machines instead of hand tools".
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] This lathe "produced screw threads out of wood and employed a true compound slide rest".
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] National Bureau of Economic Research (NBER) referenced the definition of a machine tool as "any machine operating by other than hand power which employs a tool to work on metal".
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The narrowest colloquial sense of the term reserves it only for machines that perform metal cutting—in other words, the many kinds of conventional machining and grinding.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] These processes are a type of deformation that produces swarf.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] However, economists use a slightly broader sense that also includes metal deformation of other types that squeeze the metal into shape without cutting off swarf, such as rolling, stamping with dies, shearing, swaging, riveting, and others.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Thus presses are usually included in the economic definition of machine tools.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Many reports on machine tool export and import and similar economic topics use this broader definition.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The colloquial sense implying conventional metal cutting is also growing obsolete because of changing technology over the decades.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] In addition, some of the newly developed additive manufacturing processes, which are not about cutting away material but rather about adding it, are done by machines that are likely to end up labeled, in some cases, as machine tools.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] In fact, machine tool builders are already developing machines that include both subtractive and additive manufacturing in one work envelope, and retrofits of existing machines are underway.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] In modern precision engineering, the accuracy of machine tool components is often maintained through the use of a Hirth joint.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] This coupling is the industry standard for high-accuracy positioning in components such as CNC rotary tables and tool turrets.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Its straight-tooth geometry provides maximum static stiffness and positional repeatability, ensuring that the machine maintains micron-level alignment while resisting heavy cutting forces during the machining process.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Forerunners of machine tools included bow drills and potter's wheels, which had existed in ancient Egypt prior to 2500 BC, and lathes, known to have existed in multiple regions of Europe since at least 1000 to 500 BC.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] But it was not until the later Middle Ages and the Age of Enlightenment that the modern concept of a machine tool—a class of machines used as tools in the making of metal parts, and incorporating machine-guided toolpath—began to evolve.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Clockmakers of the Middle Ages and renaissance men such as Leonardo da Vinci helped expand humans' technological milieu toward the preconditions for industrial machine tools.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] During the 18th and 19th centuries, and even in many cases in the 20th, the builders of machine tools tended to be the same people who would then use them to produce the end products (manufactured goods).
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] However, from these roots also evolved an industry of machine tool builders as we define them today, meaning people who specialize in building machine tools for sale to others.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Historians of machine tools often focus on a handful of major industries that most spurred machine tool development.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Others could be included in this list as well, but they tend to be connected with the root causes already listed.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Machine tools filled a need created by textile machinery during the Industrial Revolution in England in the middle to late 1700s.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Until that time, machinery was made mostly from wood, often including gearing and shafts.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The increase in mechanization required more metal parts, which were usually made of cast iron or wrought iron.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Cast iron could be cast in molds for larger parts, such as engine cylinders and gears, but was difficult to work with a file and could not be hammered.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Red hot wrought iron could be hammered into shapes.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Room temperature wrought iron was worked with a file and chisel and could be made into gears and other complex parts; however, hand working lacked precision and was a slow and expensive process.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] James Watt was unable to have an accurately bored cylinder for his first steam engine, trying for several years until John Wilkinson invented a suitable boring machine in 1774, boring Boulton & Watt's first commercial engine in 1776.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The advance in the accuracy of machine tools can be traced to Henry Maudslay and refined by Joseph Whitworth.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The process by which the master plane gages were produced dates back to antiquity but was refined to an unprecedented degree in the Maudslay shop.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The process begins with three square plates each given an identification (ex., 1,2 and 3).
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The first step is to rub plates 1 and 2 together with a marking medium (called bluing today) revealing the high spots which would be removed by hand scraping with a steel scraper, until no irregularities were visible.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] This would not produce true plane surfaces but a "ball and socket" concave-concave and convex-convex fit, as this mechanical fit, like two perfect planes, can slide over each other and reveal no high spots.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The rubbing and marking are repeated after rotating 2 relative to 1 by 90 degrees to eliminate concave-convex "potato-chip" curvature.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Next, plate number 3 is compared and scraped to conform to plate number 1 in the same two trials.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] In this manner plates number 2 and 3 would be identical.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Next plates number 2 and 3 would be checked against each other to determine what condition existed, either both plates were "balls" or "sockets" or "chips" or a combination.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] These would then be scraped until no high spots existed and then compared to plate number 1.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Repeating this process of comparing and scraping the three plates could produce plane surfaces accurate to within millionths of an inch (the thickness of the marking medium).
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The traditional method of producing the surface gages used an abrasive powder rubbed between the plates to remove the high spots, but it was Whitworth who contributed the refinement of replacing the grinding with hand scraping.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Sometime after 1825, Whitworth went to work for Maudslay and it was there that Whitworth perfected the hand scraping of master surface plane gages.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] With the creation of master plane gages of such high accuracy, all critical components of machine tools (i.e., guiding surfaces such as machine ways) could then be compared against them and scraped to the desired accuracy.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The first machine tools offered for sale (i.e., commercially available) were constructed by Matthew Murray in England around 1800.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Others, such as Henry Maudslay, James Nasmyth, and Joseph Whitworth, soon followed the path of expanding their entrepreneurship from manufactured end products and millwright work into the realm of building machine tools for sale.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Important early machine tools included the slide rest lathe, screw-cutting lathe, turret lathe, milling machine, pattern tracing lathe, shaper, and metal planer, which were all in use before 1840.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] With these machine tools the decades-old objective of producing interchangeable parts was finally realized.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] An important early example of something now taken for granted was the standardization of screw fasteners such as nuts and bolts.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Before about the beginning of the 19th century, these were used in pairs, and even screws of the same machine were generally not interchangeable.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Methods were developed to cut screw thread to a greater precision than that of the feed screw in the lathe being used.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] This led to the bar length standards of the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] American production of machine tools was a critical factor in the Allies' victory in World War II.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Production of machine tools tripled in the United States in the war.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] No war was more industrialized than World War II, and it has been written that the war was won as much by machine shops as by machine guns.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The production of machine tools is concentrated in about 10 countries worldwide: China, Japan, Germany, Italy, South Korea, Taiwan, Switzerland, US, Austria, Spain and a few others.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Machine tool innovation continues in several public and private research centers worldwide.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Machine tools can be powered from a variety of sources.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Human and animal power (via cranks, treadles, treadmills, or treadwheels) were used in the past, as was water power (via water wheel); however, following the development of high-pressure steam engines in the mid 19th century, factories increasingly used steam power.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Factories also used hydraulic and pneumatic power.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Many small workshops continued to use water, human and animal power until electrification after 1900.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Today most machine tools are powered by electricity; hydraulic and pneumatic power are sometimes used, but this is uncommon.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Machine tools can be operated manually, or under automatic control.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Early machines used flywheels to stabilize their motion and had complex systems of gears and levers to control the machine and the piece being worked on.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Soon after World War II, the numerical control (NC) machine was developed.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] NC machines used a series of numbers punched on paper tape or punched cards to control their motion.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] In the 1960s, computers were added to give even more flexibility to the process.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Such machines became known as computerized numerical control (CNC) machines.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] NC and CNC machines could precisely repeat sequences over and over, and could produce much more complex pieces than even the most skilled tool operators.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Before long, the machines could automatically change the specific cutting and shaping tools that were being used.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] For example, a drill machine might contain a magazine with a variety of drill bits for producing holes of various sizes.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Previously, either machine operators would usually have to manually change the bit or move the work piece to another station to perform these different operations.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The next logical step was to combine several different machine tools together, all under computer control.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] These are known as machining centers, and have dramatically changed the way parts are made.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] When fabricating or shaping parts, several techniques are used to remove unwanted metal.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Other techniques are used to *add* desired material.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] Devices that fabricate components by selective *addition* of material are called rapid prototyping machines.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The worldwide market for machine tools was approximately $81 billion in production in 2014 according to a survey by market research firm Gardner Research.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] The largest producer of machine tools was China with $23.8 billion of production followed by Germany and Japan at neck and neck with $12.9 billion and $12.88 billion respectively.
[src:mtconnect/machine-tool] South Korea and Italy rounded out the top 5 producers with revenue of $5.6 billion and $5 billion respectively.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] MES creates the "as-built" record, capturing the data, processes and outcomes of the manufacturing process.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] This can be especially important in regulated industries, such as food and beverage or pharmaceutical, where documentation and proof of processes, events and actions may be required.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] As of 2025, the manufacturing execution systems are shifting from rigid, monolithic on-premise software to modular, cloud-connected platforms.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] "Manufacturing execution systems [help] create flawless manufacturing processes and provide real-time feedback of requirement changes", and provide information at a single source.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] A wide variety of systems arose using collected data for a dedicated purpose.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Further development of these systems during the 1990s introduced overlap in functionality.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Then the Manufacturing Enterprise Solutions Association International (MESA) introduced some structure by defining 11 functions that set the scope of MES.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] In 2000, the ANSI/ISA-95 standard merged this model with the Purdue Reference Model (PRM).
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] A functional hierarchy was defined in which MES were situated at Level 3 between ERP at Level 4 and process control at Levels 0, 1, 2.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] With the publication of the third part of the standard in 2005, activities in Level 3 were divided over four main operations: production, quality, logistics and maintenance.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Between 2005 and 2013, additional or revised parts of the ANSI/ISA-95 standard defined the architecture of an MES into more detail, covering how to internally distribute functionality and what information to exchange internally as well as externally.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Over the years, international standards and models have refined the scope of such systems in terms of activities.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] MES integrates with ISA-95 (previous Purdue Reference Model, “95”) with multiple relationships.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] The collection of systems acting on the ISA-95 Level 3 can be called manufacturing operations management systems (MOMS).
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Apart from an MES, there are typically laboratory information management system (LIMS), warehouse management system (WMS) and computerized maintenance management system (CMMS).
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Examples of systems acting on ISA-95 Level 4 are product lifecycle management (PLM), enterprise resource planning (ERP), customer relationship management (CRM), human resource management (HRM), and process development execution system (PDES).
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] In many cases, middleware enterprise application integration (EAI) systems are being used to exchange transaction messages between MES and Level 4 systems.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] A common data definition, B2MML, has been defined within the ISA-95 standard to link MES systems to these Level 4 systems.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems acting on ISA-95 Level 2 are supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA), programmable logic controllers (PLC), distributed control systems (DCS) and building automation systems (BAS).
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Most MES systems include connectivity as part of their product offering.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Direct communication of plant floor equipment data is established by connecting to the PLC.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Often, plant floor data is first collected and diagnosed for real-time control in a DCS or SCADA system.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] In this case, the MES systems connect to these Level 2 systems for exchanging plant floor data.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] The industry standard for plant floor connectivity has evolved from OLE for Process Control (OPC) to OPC Unified Architecture (OPC-UA).
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Unlike its predecessor, OPC-UA is platform-independent, allowing it to run on Linux and embedded devices while offering robust security models.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] In modern Industry 4.0 architectures, MES connectivity often extends beyond the traditional hierarchy.
[src:mtconnect/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems increasingly utilize IIoT protocols like MQTT (often with Sparkplug B) to transmit lightweight data to cloud-based analytics platforms, creating a hybrid architecture where OPC-UA handles complex machine data and MQTT handles rapid telemetry.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The initiative began as a result of lectures given by David Edstrom of Sun Microsystems and David Patterson, professor of Computer Science at the University of California, Berkeley (UCB) at the 2006 annual meeting of the Association for Manufacturing Technology (AMT).
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The two lectures promoted an open communication standard to enable Internet connectivity to manufacturing equipment.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The resulting standard is available under royalty-free licensing terms.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] MTConnect is a protocol designed for the exchange of data between shop floor equipment and software applications used for monitoring and data analysis.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] MTConnect is referred to as a read-only standard, meaning that it only defines the extraction (reading) of data from control devices, not the writing of data to a control device.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] Freely available, open standards are used for all aspects of MTConnect.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] Data from shop floor devices is presented in XML format, and is retrieved from information providers, called Agents, using Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) as the underlying transport protocol.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] MTConnect provides a RESTful interface, which means the interface is stateless.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] No session must be established to retrieve data from an MTConnect Agent, and no logon or logoff sequence is required (unless overlying security protocols are added which do).
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) is recommended for discovery services.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] Version 1.0 was released in December 2008.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The first public demonstration of MTConnect occurred at the International Manufacturing Technology Show (IMTS) held in Chicago, Illinois September 2008.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] There, 25 industrial equipment manufacturers networked their machinery control systems, providing process information that could be retrieved from any web-enabled client connected to the network.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] Subsequent demonstrations occurred at EMO (the European machine tool show) in Milan, Italy in October 2009, and the 2010 IMTS in Chicago.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The MTConnect standard has three sections.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The first section provides information on the protocol and structure of the XML documents via XML schemas.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The second section specifies the machine tool components and the description of the available data.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The third and last section specifies the organization of the data streams that can be provided from a manufacturing device.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The MTConnect Institute is considering adding a fourth section to support mobile assets that include tools and work-holdings.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] MTConnect took an incremental approach to defining the requirements for manufacturing device communications.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] It did not exhaustively define every possible piece of data an application can collect from a manufacturing device, but it works forward from business and research objectives to define the required elements to meet those needs.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The standard catalogued important components and data items for metal cutting devices.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] MTConnect provides an extensible XML schema to allow implementors to add custom data to meet their specific needs, while providing as much commonality as possible.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] On September 16, 2010, The MTConnect Institute and the OPC Foundation announced cooperation between the respective organizations.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The maintenance cost and losses in productivity with unplanned downtime for machine tool components such as spindle bearings and ball screws could be reduced if one could proactively take action prior to failure.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] In addition, cutting tools and inserts are expensive to replace when they are still in good condition, but replacing the tools too late can be costly due to scrap and re-work.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The proposed health monitoring application will use MTConnect to extract controller data and pattern recognition algorithms to assess the health condition of the spindle and machine tool axes.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] The health assessment approach is based on running a routine program each shift in which the most recent data patterns are compared to the baseline data patterns.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] An online tool condition monitoring module is also proposed and uses controller data such as the spindle motor current, with other add on sensors (vibration, acoustic emission) to accurately estimate and predict tool wear.
[src:mtconnect/mtconnect] With the added transparency of the machine tool health information, one can take proactive actions before significant downtime or productivity losses occur.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Measuring OEE is a manufacturing best practice.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] By measuring OEE and the underlying losses, important insights can be gained on how to systematically improve the manufacturing process.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Technically, OEE is an effective metric for identifying and visualizing losses, and steering the improvement of the effectiveness of manufacturing equipment by eliminating 'waste'.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Socially, OEE can provide a common language for groups speaking in different 'languages' such as shop floor (units), managers (money) or planners (time).
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The term OEE was first mentioned in Seiichi Nakajima's book 'TPM Tenkai' in 1982.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE was described as a central part of the Total Productive Maintenance methodology.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is based on the Harrington Emerson way of thinking regarding labor efficiency.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] 100% OEE is considered to be a theoretical reference point where a machine would be permanently running, at its theoretical maximal speed, producing only good products.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Anything hindering this is considered to be a 'loss'.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] When running: Is the machine running at theoretical maximal speed?
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Is the output meeting its specifications?
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The first question leads to the 'availabilty rate' of the equipment, the second one to the 'performance rate' and the third one to the 'quality rate'.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] in this way, a cascade of effectiveness and effectiveness losses arises.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The quality rate refers to a part of the performance (the part that there was 'speed', the other part is lost in the performance rate).
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Performance rate refers to part of the availability (the time there was output - the other part is lost in the availability rate).
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Each of the three components of the OEE points to an aspect of the process that can be targeted for improvement.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE may be applied to any individual equipment or line.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This tool also allows for drilling down for very specific analysis, such as a particular Time frame, Shift, Team or any of several other parameters.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Although the performance of a particular product can be determined from OEE data, OEE cannot be calculated for that product because this would require that all downtime (availability losses) should be correlated to specific products.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE focusses on the 'if not' in the equations: Where did potential effectiveness got lost?
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] These 'losses' of effectiveness are being subdivided further into what is known as the 'Six Big Losses' to OEE.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to make this more universally applicable and also to better reflect the financial impact of the losses, the original six big losses were later adjusted slightly.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The reason for identifying the losses in these categories is so that specific countermeasures can be applied to reduce the loss and improve the overall OEE.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Multiplying the three underlying grades AxPxQ results in a percentage value that indicates the proportion of the scheduled machine running time during which production actually met the quality criteria.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This value is always well below 100%, as 100% is a theoretical value.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Even if a system runs continuously at maximum speed without causing a single defect, it will for example still need to be serviced at some point.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Alternatively, the OEE as a number could be calculated by dividing the minimum time needed to produce the parts under optimal conditions by the actual time needed to produce the parts.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] However, in this way the losses are no longer known, meaning the most important part of OEE is missing.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The value range for OEE is between 0% and 100%.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If an effectiveness level of more than 100% is displayed, this indicates an error in the definition.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Availability portion of the OEE Metric represents the percentage of scheduled time (also referred to as 'loading time') that the equipment is available to operate.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given machine is scheduled to run for an 8-hour (480-minute) shift with a 30-minute break, during which the machine is being stopped, and there is a breakdown of 60 minutes.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] During the scheduled operating time of 480 minutes, the machine was waiting 30 min. because of the break and 60 minutes because it broke down.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The performance rate represents the ratio between the theoretical maximum speed of the machine and its actual speed.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Performance can only be calculated when there is output; thus during actual running time.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] While the actual performance can be measured, it is often difficult in operational practice to obtain the theoretical maximum speed as a reference value.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The technical data provided by the machine manufacturer does not usually correspond to the theoretically possible maximum values, e.g. to avoid complaints or for other reasons.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Defining a too low maximum speed will become visible when the performance goes above 100%, which is undesirable.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Ultimately, the goal of OEE is to reveal all potential.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is a good practice to calculate the maximum value based on physical limits, e.g., a calculation of heat transfer, the power of a motor, or the fall speed of a product.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If that fails, the concept of "best demonstrated cycle time" has proven itself.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This involves determining the production speeds of products from the past and increasing the highest production speed by a margin of 20%.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Defining this as 100% performance may lead to a structurally too low OEE, however it will visualize any potential loss on the performance.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The factor 1 (100%) now represents a peak value that is never exceeded, even for a short time.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For systems that only manufacture one or a few products, calculating the performance factor is simple.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If a large number of different products with different maximum speeds are run on one system (multi-product companies), the effort required to determine the maximum speed can be high and the performance should be calculated correctly using a weighted average.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given equipment is scheduled to run for an 8-hour (480-minute) and has 90 min downtime.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The equipment produces 242 Total Units during the shift.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Note: The basis is Total Units, not Good Units.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Performance metric does not penalize for Quality.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Quality portion of the OEE Metric represents the Good Units produced as a percentage of the Total Units produced.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Quality Metric is a pure measurement of Process Yield that is designed to exclude the effects of Availability and Performance.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The losses due to defects and rework are called *quality losses*.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The calculations of OEE may not seem to be particularly complicated, but care must be taken as to standards that are used as the basis.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to visualize all losses, it is crucial to use the right 'configuration' of the metric.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Definitions — for parts — of the OEE can be found in ISO 22400-2:2014. and VDI 3423:2011-08 (2011) These definitions are not standardized for all industries and are individually tailored to the respective company in its application.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Furthermore, the ISO 22400 standard presents two different OEE versions that appear to be inconsistent with one another, the first of which – in the standard's normative section – contains no reference to or connection with the original Nakajima's Total Productive Maintenance (TPM) model.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To resolve this ambiguity, academic literature provides a comprehensive classification framework that maps the standard's time elements to the traditional OEE formula, ensuring consistency between the ISO standard and established industrial practices.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This to OEE dedicated standard aims for the visualisation of all effectiveness losses on any manufacturing equipment, being unabigiously clear to production personnel.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The standard uses the same logic and uniform terminology for any type of equipment.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to calculate OEE, operational data needs to be acquired from the production process.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This needs to reflect 'what happened' on one hand, and 'what did not happen' (the losses) on the other hand.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Depending on the systems or products, it can be difficult to collect the basic data required to determine the key figure.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Many companies therefore rely on special software for data collection.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The goal of TPM (Total Productive Maintenance) as set out by Seiichi Nakajima, is "The continuous improvement of OEE by engaging all those that impact on it in small group activities".
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To achieve this, the TPM toolbox sets out a Focused improvement tactic to reduce each of the six types of OEE loss.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For example, the Focused improvement tactic to systematically reduce breakdown risk sets out how to improve asset condition and standardise working methods to reduce human error and accelerated wear.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Zero Failure Management provides a profound structure to achieve this.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Combining OEE with Focused improvement converts OEE from a lagging to a leading indicator that can be used to guide performance management priorities.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The first Focused improvement stage of OEE improvement is to achieve a stable OEE, i.e. one which varies at around 5% from the mean for a representative production sample.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This indicates that the asset performance is stable and not affected by variability in equipment wear rates and working methods.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The second stage of OEE improvement (optimisation) is meant to remove chronic losses.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] As the TPM process delivers these gains through small cross functional improvement teams, the process of OEE improvement should also raise front line team engagement, problem ownership, collaboration and skill levels.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This combination of OEE as a KPI, TPM Focused improvement tactics and front line team engagement is intended to make the gains sustainable and deliver the TPM goal of year on year improvement in OEE.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Zero Failure Management helps significantly to achieve this.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE measurement is also commonly used as a key performance indicator (KPI) in conjunction with lean manufacturing efforts.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To achieve the main goal of Lean, creating flow, individual pieces of equipment need to be fully reliable and in tune.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] TEEP, therefore, reports the 'bottom line' effectiveness of manufacturing equipment.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To calculate the Total Effective Equipment Performance(TEEP), the OEE is multiplied by a fourth component: Loading.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Loading rate of the TEEP Metric represents the percentage of time that the equipment is scheduled to operate compared to the total Calendar Time that is available.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Loading Metric is a pure measurement of Schedule effectiveness and is designed to exclude the effects how well that equipment may perform.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given equipment is scheduled to run 5 Days per Week, 24 Hours per Day.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For a given week, the Total Calendar Time is 7 Days at 24 Hours.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The advantage of OEE lies in the transparency of the value added share and the associated losses of the equipment.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The term "Overall Equipment Efficiency" is often wrongly used as a synonym for "Overall Equipment Effectiveness".
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Measures that increase production output but incur disproportionately high costs may well be effective, but at the same time they may be inefficient and therefore economically unviable and thus unproductive.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Often, insufficient quality is not detected at the equipment that caused it.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In this case, it has proven effective to apply the "discovery principle," i.e., to apply an OEE reduction to the equipment where the error was discovered.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This removes the OEE from being purely equipment-related and turns it into a process indicator.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] However, the OEE of a piece of equipment can of course also be optimized by making improvements to other equipment.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The OEE should also be a key figure that is as up-to-date as possible.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In this respect, the OK quantity should be determined at the latest at the end of the shift and the OEE calculated.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] From the perspective of Process Control, the question rises how an operator can be responsible for manufacturing correct products if he cannot see whether the products are correct.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To highlight this problem, it is worth considering blocked products as a quality issue: after all, they were not right the first time around.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Valuable activities such as setup or maintenance will also reduce overall equipment effectiveness (OEE) at the beginning.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If setup activities reduce overall equipment effectiveness, there is an incentive to reduce setup times using SMED (Single-minute exchange of die).
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] On the other hand, this also means that OEE can be increased by reducing the number of changeovers, i.e. by increasing batch sizes.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This would contradict the principles of lean production.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This highlights the importance of a clear explanation of OEE: the goal is not to be as high as possible, but to identify obstacles and then eliminate them.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A convention must be agreed within the company to define when downtime occurs.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Recording and justifying every second of equipment downtime is too time-consuming for most companies.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In practice, a recording limit of 1 to 5 minutes of equipment downtime has proven to be a pragmatic approach.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] All downtimes of less than one minute are therefore included in the performance rate.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The collected data must be processed in order to obtain meaningful information.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This information is aimed at various target groups, such as.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Meaningful analyses prove to be the key to good decisions.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Theoretically, this is only possible with very precise figures.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In practice, it has been shown that correctly selected data has a greater effect in this respect than high precision.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Although tempting, OEE (as a number) is NOT suitable for comparing machines or benchmarking.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For similar reasons, OEE may not be applied to aggregate to Department or Plant levels.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Where multiple machines are linked together, each individual piece of equipment will display the waiting categories "No Input" (Starved) and "No output" (Blocked) in addition to the standard standstill reasons.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This allows upstream or downstream faults in production equipment to be identified.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The use of OEE requires knowledge of manufacturing environments and understanding of the underlying data.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Without this, a specific OEE number may be of little to no value.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE cannot be used to measure employee performance.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is used to identify and measure equipment losses, which can then be eliminated through appropriate root cause analysis and measures.
[src:mtconnect/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Using OEE as a heuristic is not recommended.
